\chapter{QR Codes}

The QR module is intentionally thin.  The interesting design decision happened
earlier: we chose [[segno]] because it stays in pure Python and writes PDF files
directly, which keeps the slide-generation path dependency-light.

There is one twist on top of plain QR generation.  Slides used to print the
URL beneath the QR code as a separate LaTeX snippet, computed at the same time
as the QR file but emitted into the [[.tex]] output as its own
[[\texttt]]-formatted line.  When [[mentipy serve]] later regenerates the QR
PDFs to point at a freshly resolved address (LAN, UPnP, SSH tunnel), only the
PDF on disk is updated; the printed URL is frozen in whatever the previous
compile chose.  The two artifacts can drift, and respondents see a QR that
scans to one place and a label that reads another.

We close the gap by following Inkscape's [[.pdf_tex]] export pattern.  Each
question now owns \emph{two} on-disk artifacts that are always written
together: the QR PDF, and a tiny sidecar LaTeX file that [[\input]]s the PDF
and renders the URL caption beneath it.  Slides include the sidecar; the QR
matrix and the printed URL are produced by a single call to [[make_qr]] and
cannot diverge.  When [[regenerate_qrs]] later refreshes the QRs, the sidecars
are refreshed in the same loop---no extra plumbing required.

